1
00:00:47,833 --> 00:00:48,666
Dad.

2
00:00:57,041 --> 00:00:58,166
What are you up to?

3
00:01:01,958 --> 00:01:02,791
Dad.

4
00:01:03,458 --> 00:01:04,625
What are you doing?

5
00:01:09,708 --> 00:01:10,625
Dad.

6
00:01:11,541 --> 00:01:12,458
What's wrong?

7
00:01:13,041 --> 00:01:14,541
It's me, Le-le.

8
00:01:18,583 --> 00:01:19,583
I'm fine.

9
00:01:44,958 --> 00:01:51,791
DELIRIUM

10
00:01:59,291 --> 00:02:00,208
Okay, done.

11
00:02:01,500 --> 00:02:02,666
He's…

12
00:02:03,500 --> 00:02:05,750
Some time ago, he'd stare at one spot

13
00:02:05,833 --> 00:02:08,666
and mumble to himself
or stay quiet for a long time.

14
00:02:08,750 --> 00:02:12,000
The other day at the store,
he couldn't recognize me.

15
00:02:12,083 --> 00:02:17,916
And yesterday, he went
to my old elementary school to pick me up.

16
00:02:18,416 --> 00:02:23,291
I know he has mild dementia,
but he was doing okay before.

17
00:02:23,375 --> 00:02:25,333
I don't know why it suddenly got worse.

18
00:02:25,416 --> 00:02:29,666
Has anything changed in his life lately?
Like moving or having arguments?

19
00:02:31,458 --> 00:02:32,458
No…

20
00:02:33,250 --> 00:02:36,041
I helped him tidy up his place.
Does that count?

21
00:02:36,125 --> 00:02:40,291
The elderly often rely on
certain habits or routines in their lives.

22
00:02:40,375 --> 00:02:43,125
We might think
we mean well by tidying up for them,

23
00:02:43,208 --> 00:02:45,791
but it backfires
and they can't recognize anything.

24
00:02:46,625 --> 00:02:47,833
I see.

25
00:02:48,875 --> 00:02:51,708
Besides the changes in his surroundings,

26
00:02:51,791 --> 00:02:55,291
has anything happened
that you think is significant?

27
00:02:55,375 --> 00:02:56,916
I don't think so…

28
00:02:58,125 --> 00:02:59,416
Oh, I…

29
00:03:00,458 --> 00:03:04,166
My mom passed away recently,
and so did his best friend.

30
00:03:04,250 --> 00:03:07,500
That's pretty significant.
Why wouldn't you see it as a change?

31
00:03:08,041 --> 00:03:10,666
He and my mom
have been divorced for over 30 years.

32
00:03:10,750 --> 00:03:12,291
And they don't live together.

33
00:03:12,375 --> 00:03:15,083
The day he came back
from his friend's funeral…

34
00:03:15,166 --> 00:03:19,083
Actually… It seemed like
he was still able to joke around.

35
00:03:19,166 --> 00:03:22,958
Living apart and not meeting often
doesn't mean there's no bond.

36
00:03:23,041 --> 00:03:25,333
He might not have
expressed certain emotions,

37
00:03:25,416 --> 00:03:27,833
but he's really hurting inside.

38
00:03:27,916 --> 00:03:32,333
This type of PTSD can sometimes
speed up the progression of dementia.

39
00:03:32,416 --> 00:03:35,250
It could even result in delirium.

40
00:03:35,750 --> 00:03:37,625
Excuse me, what's that?

41
00:03:38,333 --> 00:03:41,291
Delirium is an acute brain failure.

42
00:03:41,375 --> 00:03:43,250
So, it's not related to dementia?

43
00:03:43,333 --> 00:03:45,333
It's similar, but people confuse the two.

44
00:03:45,416 --> 00:03:48,583
But delirium
is more of an acute brain illness.

45
00:03:48,666 --> 00:03:51,416
It can be controlled
through early treatment.

46
00:03:52,208 --> 00:03:55,791
Gosh. How many
more of these old-age diseases are there?

47
00:03:56,875 --> 00:03:57,875
Bed coming through.

48
00:03:57,958 --> 00:03:59,458
Excuse me, coming through.

49
00:04:06,833 --> 00:04:09,208
- Bed coming through.
- Excuse me, coming through.

50
00:04:09,875 --> 00:04:11,375
Dad, let's go.

51
00:04:15,500 --> 00:04:16,625
I don't want

52
00:04:17,416 --> 00:04:19,750
to be hooked up to all those tubes.

53
00:04:20,625 --> 00:04:22,375
Why are you saying that?

54
00:04:24,416 --> 00:04:25,750
Just a minute, please.

55
00:04:30,208 --> 00:04:31,833
- Name, please?
- Cheng Kuang-chi.

56
00:04:32,750 --> 00:04:33,708
Thank you.

57
00:04:33,791 --> 00:04:35,708
This medicine's for calming the brain.

58
00:04:35,791 --> 00:04:37,041
Take one before bed.

59
00:04:37,125 --> 00:04:39,125
- This one's for the stomach.
- Okay.

60
00:04:39,208 --> 00:04:40,541
- Thanks.
- No problem.

61
00:04:55,291 --> 00:04:57,333
- Let go. Look closely.
- It's my bike.

62
00:04:57,416 --> 00:04:58,583
- It's mine.
- I just…

63
00:04:58,666 --> 00:05:00,458
- What's going on?
- It's mine.

64
00:05:00,541 --> 00:05:02,291
It's mine, but he keeps saying it's his.

65
00:05:02,375 --> 00:05:03,625
- It isn't your bike.
- It is.

66
00:05:03,708 --> 00:05:05,625
- It's mine. Stop it!
- Sorry, he's confused.

67
00:05:05,708 --> 00:05:08,250
- You rode your bike to Mr. Tang's funeral.
- Let go!

68
00:05:08,333 --> 00:05:09,375
Did you ride it back?

69
00:05:09,458 --> 00:05:11,625
Are you senile or what?

70
00:05:11,708 --> 00:05:13,000
Did you have to be so rough?

71
00:05:13,083 --> 00:05:14,958
- He has some issues…
- I'm in a hurry.

72
00:05:15,041 --> 00:05:16,125
Why's that my problem?

73
00:05:16,208 --> 00:05:18,541
- He didn't mean to.
- Was it my fault? Why yell?

74
00:05:18,625 --> 00:05:20,666
- All right, guys.
- Can we respect each other?

75
00:05:20,750 --> 00:05:23,458
- He's having some issues.
- "Respect?" What a joke!

76
00:05:23,541 --> 00:05:24,416
Did you respect me?

77
00:05:24,500 --> 00:05:25,750
- Stop arguing.
- Fine, sorry.

78
00:05:25,833 --> 00:05:27,208
I'm so sorry, all right?

79
00:05:27,291 --> 00:05:28,291
Sorry to bother you.

80
00:05:29,208 --> 00:05:30,041
I apologize.

81
00:05:30,125 --> 00:05:31,666
What a bunch of lunatics.

82
00:05:35,750 --> 00:05:37,458
I'm sorry.

83
00:05:38,958 --> 00:05:39,791
Dad.

84
00:05:40,291 --> 00:05:41,708
Where are you going now?

85
00:06:51,083 --> 00:06:54,500
PERIOD CLUB MEETING AT 14:00 TOMORROW

86
